In a statement released on Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that by drastically changing the course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA's obligation to cooperate with the States in a comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
"In previous administrations, the EPA was often unable to meet the deadlines, then waited for action from groups of activists and others and discussed the timing of the case," said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA at his previous Post.
"We do not believe in regulation through litigation, and we treat the deadlines seriously.
We are also serious about our charter and the power it gives us. "
However, the EPA statement states that Pruitt may at some point again use its "powers to defer and other legal credentials" to make sure that the Norms "Jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information".
