The president will determine the order and place of the oath
Where and how the new Russian citizens will be swearing allegiance to the Russian Federation, will determine the President-such amendments to the second reading in the relevant law was developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and state.
A week ago the deputies planned to define the order of swearing in the law directly.
From the solemn oath will be released children under 18 years of age, as well as incapacitated, follows from the amended text of amendments to the Bill "on citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available "Izvestia"), which the Committee on July 11 will consider before the second reading on its meeting.
The idea of imposing an oath of allegiance to the Russian Federation instead of the formal signing of the documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on June 6 during a meeting with the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies have made this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill, which provides for the abolition of the decision on the extradition of nationality to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public Calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (H. 2 art. 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for hijacking a plane, train or water transport, but only if the act is connected with terrorism (Part 4 art. 211 of the Russian Criminal Code).
According to the bill, his logic was as follows: When issuing documents for citizenship, a person subscribes under the promise to abide by Russian legislation-embarking on the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
The bill in April brought to the Duma leaders of Duma fractions Vladimir Vasilyev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (Communist), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergey Mironov ("Fair Russia") and the Speaker of the DG Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19 deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the Committee on State and legislation approved the text of the bill for second reading, but now it has been reworked again.
Now it says that the order of swearing will be set by the President of the Russian Federation.
Previously, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "on citizenship of the Russian Federation", stating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn atmosphere before the state emblem and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Interior Ministry.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place-the list of places where the emblem of the Russian Federation may be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, cabinets of heads of bodies of sings entities, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive authorities, etc.
Most likely, it could be registry.
To pronounce solemn oath wishing to receive citizenship of the Russian Federation will be after officials have checked their documents.
But the person will receive the Russian passport only after the oath, follows from the modified text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that the swearing of Russia will be 18 years old, not 14.
There is a rule that the oath will be exempted from incapacitated or incapacitated, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or personally sign the text of the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure and "other persons",
Also, the updated Bill prescribes a special procedure for admission to Russian citizens of Ukrainian residents, who are considered native Russian speakers.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship by providing a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
The waiver of "alien" nationality, as it is now, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is not possible "for reasons beyond the person's power".
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including the first vice-speaker of the DG Ivan Melnikov (Communist), Natalia Bowing, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ira Farrahov (All-"United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, just impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for a solution to their fate about the citizenship of the Russian Federation,-explained the day before the head of the Duma Committee on state and Legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (EP).
In addition, the text clarified that restrictions on the employment of certain positions for foreigners would not be extended to those who refused "other" citizenship in writing and passed the previous passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but "on the independent of it Reasons, "he was not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in the municipal service, to be accepted for work on objects and in the organizations which activity is connected with maintenance of security of Russia.
Also a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country can not become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should enter into force on September 1, 2017, by that time the necessary bylaws should be ready.
