Judges are invited to protect from the presidents
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judicial branch of government.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the court presidents and to impose their election.
For courts of appeal and cassation instance, the HRC wants to introduce special constituencies that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential order.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was conducted by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the President gave after meeting with council members.
At the meeting with the Council members on December 8, 2016 were discussed including individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see "Kommersant" on December 9).
The work of the HRC resulted in 25 proposals, which relate to the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the court presidents to increase the independence of the remaining judges.
If the candidate for the position of the judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, the President of the Court, in the opinion of the HRC, should submit it to the appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed that the President be deprived of the right to distribute cases between judges.
To do it, allow experts, can specially written computer program.
Also, the HRC believes that the Chairman is not entitled to "predetermine the results of the qualification evaluation of the judge, to initiate his involvement in disciplinary responsibility, to make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to the "election of the Presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "to confer powers on them for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all the presidents of the courts (from the Republican to the district) are appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the Chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to shield judges from the pressures of regional administrations, the HRC proposes a new appeal and appeal in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instance not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts".
Experts take the practice of arbitration courts as a basis.
They have "judicial districts", which do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee at the expense of this greater independence from regional officials, who are hampered by the use of "telephone law".
Magistrates of the HRC proposes to strengthen the people's jury to consider some "categories of civil and administrative cases" with their participation.
For example, deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement at work, protection of honor and dignity, denial of driving licences, etc.
"These are only our proposals," said the member of the HRC, the judge of the Constitutional Court in resignation Tamara Morshhakova.
She also recalled that the President's assignment concerned not only the HRC but also the Supreme Court (SC), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
The time to carry out the task of the Sun (among the co-prosecutors and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation) is still there.
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in Russia, the chairman of the Sun Vyacheslav Lebedev should be by September 1.
