Italy is tightening its tone towards the ships of NGOs rescuing migrants.
Italy warned NGOs that owned rescue ships in the Mediterranean that they would not be able to continue their work unless obey new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not obey the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," said Interior Minister Mario Minniti in an interview with the Turin daily newspaper "Stampa".
The Minniti warning sounded the following day after the Italian authorities confiscated a vessel belonging to the German humanitarian organization "Jugend Rettet", on suspicion that its crew actually cooperated with traffickers and Facilitates illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has worked for the whole year, has refused to comment on the merits of the detailed accusations made against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Kartozio.
"For us the salvation of human life is and will remain the highest priority, so we are very sorry that we can not continue activities in the area of search and rescue,"-says the organization's statement in social networks.
"We will be able to assess all the accusations made now, only after we gather all the information and evaluate the situation."
Italian authorities are watching the ship "Yuventa" belonging to "Jugend Rettet", since October.
His crew is suspected of having taken on board migrants whom traffickers sent directly to them and allowed the smugglers to leave together with boats that they could use anew.
At least one such meeting is expected to take place only 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, as alleged in the charges, the contents of which were published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coast authorities, which control the rescue operations in this zone, rather of humanitarian zeal, than for any other motive.
The code of conduct presupposes, mainly, that vessels of the type "Juventy" will have on board an Italian police officer who will monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to obey the code: "Save the Children", Maltese MOAS and "Pro-Activa outstretched hugs" from Spain.
The latter stated on Thursday that it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable provided that they did not entail any "significant changes or hindrances" to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is also a Nobel Prize organization Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said that the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan Coast Guard and cooperation with local mayors are bearing fruit.
"In the last days we began to see the light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
He reported on plans for further negotiations with the Libyan Mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
