Resident Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years of imprisonment for using text messages and phone calls encouraged to kill her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to be 15 months behind bars and five more years of probation.
Carter was convicted in June of the manslaughter murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on 13 July 2014.
Roy's father said at the Thursday's hearing, "My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend. "
Carter was allowed to stay free before the appeal.
She threatened a maximum of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, compressing hands and drooping eyes.
"She killed Conrad Roy by her actions," the prosecutor said to the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her.
She did not recognize responsibility, "she said.
"She has not demonstrated remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was a "tragic case she deeply regrets."
Judge Lawrence Monis said, however, that in his opinion, her "age, maturity, or even mental illness did not have a noticeable impact on her actions".
The prosecutor read out a statement from Roy Lynn Roy's mother, saying: "There has not been a single day when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I manage-I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever, "-said in him.
Roy Kamdin Roy's sister said that she was haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become an aunt of his children.
"To lose a man who has been with me ever since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to become a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide for the responsibility of a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of monoxide gas poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide of the Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump from the roof, stab yourself with a knife do not know there are many ways,"-she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before the suicide she wrote: "You have to do it, Conrad" and "You just need to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monit said Carter wanted to catch up with Roy's death and forbade her from communicating with the press to prevent her from getting the desired.
The opinions of the lawyers were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
30-year-old Knox published in the Los Angeles Times his special opinion, which stated: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
