"I could just touch a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700-1980s by a double agent working for Jacobite," he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those days the lights were lit.
And in 300 years, in the future, you think you're there too.
Oh, how I love archives! "
For a person covered by such a passion for old papers, get support from the National Foundation and the English Texbook Council and live in the castle for four months ("Frankly, I'm a little zagostilsja there") seems too good to be True.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, walked through the archives and considered numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things-for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles, centuries lain in moat.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talked to wardens, gardeners and sometimes with artists who worked on illustrations to his book.
Then at night he "drank whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scotney Castle is not very much studied, because the National fund got full access to it only in 2006 when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived in ten years, the staff were only beginning to deal with the archive, which he described as "what the aristocrats piled to the attic for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," Rhodes says, "but here's the birch that two families fought for.
It happens so, guys! "
In some of the stories of the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for broader research in English history: for example, in the "worker", the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the peasant revolution of 1381 years.
"There is evidence of a riot that took place in the castle in the year 1380, in a book called" The Knights of Kent and Sussex, "says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising began in these places, and I thought the riot was a good start.
Maybe they were connected? "
Other subjects are strongly related to the history of the castle-for example, "Priest", which tells about a Jesuit priest, whom the family Darrelov seven years hid at home during the English Reformation.
or "smuggler", about the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to faked his own funeral, with stones in the coffin (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug).
Darrely-The favorite family Rhodes of all that inhabited Scotney: "Gentlemen, it seems, were perfect zhulem, always therefor into debt and spend money on something that could not afford.
In different generations men-darrely solved their problems with debts, marrying wealthy elderly women-I imagine them as a company of cute guys who are able to care for the heirs of large states. "
After finishing work at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to get a unique writing experience.
He lived two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Jeljamjanmjaki-a place where in the early XX century was a sanatorium, and then it grew again forest.
But Scotney remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like this: damn it, I have to go back to real life again."
