Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help ease the GCS.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve the symptoms of those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the United States and 300000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually to mitigate symptoms patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase Bowel tolerance.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the immune cells in the intestines ensure that the harmful microbes coming with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells that can trigger an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body while not damaging sensitive tissues.
If the equilibrium is too severely disturbed in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice having a certain bacterium in the intestines, appear increasing tolerance cells.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan--one of the building elements of protein--to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one type of bacteria-Lactobacillus reuteri-which is part of the normal microbiome of the intestine, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan contained in the nutrition of mice, the more these immune cells they had. "
He suggested that the same would work for people: the combination of L. reuteri and a rich tryptophan diet can contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation in the intestines.
Postdoc Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying the variety of immune cells that increase tolerance, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, while another group that belonged to the same line, but contained separately, did not Was.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the mikrobiomami of the gut mice-communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA cells of the mice were sequenced, and six species of bacteria were found in mice that had immune cells but were absent from mice without them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment, had no good microbiome and did not developed this type of immune cells, received L. reuteri, and the immune cells they have appeared.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of liquid-without bacteria-to nedorazvivshimsja immune cells, separated from the mice.
The immune cells have turned into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of the processing of tryptophan, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in food mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells also dropped twice.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri the development of cells in humans as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in the genes associated with tryptophan were found.
She says: "Perhaps the development of these cells should be strengthened, because the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. Reuteri can potentially lead to the expansion of their population. "
