Disabled Anton Mamaev appointed fine
Moscow softened the punishment of the disabled wheelchair Anton Mamaev from four and a half years of imprisonment to a fine of 200 thousand. Rub.
Earlier by the decision of the Timiryazevsky court the convict was released from the remand prison.
At the same time, Moscow confirmed that the accused is a criminal, as he organized robbery and kidnapping of a scooter from a former special forces fighter.
Moscow his decision to soften the punishment of Anton Mamaev to 200 thousand. Rub. Fine.
"Mamas is the organizer of the robbery, which also forms the composition of the crime, and, accordingly, such a person should be brought to criminal responsibility,"-explained "Kommersant" spokesman Mosgorsuda Hive Solopova.
In this case the court took into account the state of health of Mamaeva, factual circumstances of the case, absence of aggravating circumstances.
In addition, the court applied art. 64 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation, according to which it is possible to assign punishment below the lower limit.
As for the assistant Mamaeva Vasily Seroshtanova, the court did not establish the circumstances which would be the basis for changing the category of gravity of the offense and changing the sentence.
Anton Mamas himself said that he was unhappy with the decision of Mosgorsuda.
I'm disappointed with the court's decision.
The only legitimate solution would be an excuse, intending to further fight for justice.
His lawyer Andrei Orlov did not rule out appeal against the verdict in the cassation instance of Mosgorsuda and the Supreme Court.
"We will use all levers up to the European Court of Human Rights," he told RIA Novosti.
Recall, 28-year-old Muscovite Anton Mamas, suffering from spinal muscular atrophy, became the defendant of the criminal case in the autumn of last year.
A disabled person claims to have bought a scooter from acquaintances for 160 thousand. Rub to then sell.
However, the owners of the scooter, among whom-a former special forces fighter, said that the disabled and his assistant Vasily Seroshtanov confiscated their property, threatening to use violence.
On June 30 Timirjazevskij District Court of Moscow sentenced Vasily Seroshtanova to three years of the colony, and Anton Mamaeva to four and a half years of imprisonment with serving punishment in the colony of General regime (under Part 2 of article 162 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
After the Ryujo disabled person was placed in the remand prison, the public Chamber, the Prosecutor General's Office, the Presidential Commissioner for Human Rights Tatiana Moskalkova joined the case.
As a result, in the middle of July Anton Mamas was released from the remand prison by the decision of the same Timiryazevsky court.
The defense, in turn, appealed the decision of the first instance in city.
