White House props to taxpayers in thousands of dollars
According to the military records given to the TIME magazine, the decision of the White House last month to drive a marine infantry helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers Whole 24 000 dollars.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3d, known as the "Marine One", when the president is on board, has become a central element in the White House's July 17 event, which showcased American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, vice president Mike Pence and top officials of the White House inspected technological products from all fifty states.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was exhibited next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the first squadron of Marine helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for helicopter management, the White House military authority ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or "Frago", just 36 hours before The helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to be convinced that you are aware of this, because it is an unusual event widely illuminated in the press," wrote Commander HMX-1 in an e-mail to his boss, the first Deputy chief of Aviation of the Marine Corps, the day before Events.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and remain there until the lawn was vacated between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the restrictions on the working hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event and the security officers remained near the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It remains unclear from the records received by TIME magazine whether the second crew was required.
The Hatch law prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the action contradicted the decision.
"Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of the law hatch, and we were told that there is no," the commander wrote.
"It seems that you have nowhere to go," the deputy head said.
The "Made in America" event was declared a White House as an official event, and the hatch law was not distributed to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the reform of health, which was at that time in the development of the Senate, and praise attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are instructed to use them for travel.
But to request them solely in the interest of photoability is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February, when a presidential plane drove in the background during his first pre-election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was inundated with complaints about the use of the presidential Aircraft by its predecessor.
"The White House is delighted with the" Made in America "show, which showcased products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said deputy spokesman for White House Lindsay Walters.
The HMX-1 crews often carry out training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to train the president of the United States in the White House with an accuracy of up to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 held 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the event "Made in America" was counted to the crew in the account of necessary training flights for a month.
The unit's helicopters that day also flew 11 additional hours as part of the "Nonpresidential support Tasks".
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not cost any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
The representative of the company "Sikorsky" reported that the company did not participate in the organization of the helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the hourly rates of the Ministry of Defense for 2017 fiscal year, the rate of reimbursement of the Ministry of Defense for VH-3d is 24 380 USD per hour of flight.
In the records of the unit, it was recorded that the time of the aircraft in the air amounted to 30 minutes in each direction from its base airfield on the aviation base of the Marine Corps Quantico in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
"Calculating the value for taxpayers based on the approximate rate of reimbursement is totally wrong," Walters said.
"These approximate rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual Assignirovanija."
According to a study conducted in 2015 by RAND Corporation, the rates of reimbursement do not include the cost of the personnel, but indeed take into account the cost of fuel, services and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, a former White House spokesman, Sean Spicer, spoke in defense of the helicopter's use for the event.
"The idea is to demonstrate this week the things made in America," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I guess, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that has been relentlessly workeded by so many Americans.
So, of course, it is quite appropriate to pay attention to this. "
It was unclear whether Trump was interacting with the helicopter while viewing the southern lawn during the event, but he was definitely sitting in a driver place in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump appealed to the representatives of the company "Sikorsky", joking with the press on the theme of his own fleet of products of the company.
"I know Sikorsky well," the president said. "I have three of them."
